h dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n[[Category:English male short story writers]]\n[[Category:English short story writers]]\n[[Category:Heidelberg University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hindu\u2013German Conspiracy]]\n[[Category:LGBT dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:LGBT novelists]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from England]]\n[[Category:Maugham family|W. Somerset Maugham]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the Companions of Honour]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Canterbury]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:People with speech impediment]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Victorian novelists]]\n[[Category:World War I spies for the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "14.248.147.84", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._Somerset_Maugham"}
{"title_page": "Yanny or Laurel", "text_new": "{{pp-pc}}\n{{redirect|Yanny|other uses|Yanni (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|voice recording containing an auditory illusion and made popular in May 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Listen|type=Music|filename=YannyLaurel.ogg|title=Laurel|description=This low quality recording of the pronunciation of \"Laurel\", which went viral on Twitter, enhances the illusion according to Brad Story.<ref name=CNN/>{{Verify source|date=May 2018}}}}\n'''\"Yanny or Laurel\"''' is an [[auditory illusion]] of a re-recording of a vocabulary word plus added background sounds, also mixed into the recording, which became popular in May 2018.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news |last= Kirby |first=Jen |title= Why you hear \"Laurel\" or \"Yanny\" in that viral audio clip, explained |url= https://www.vox.com/2018/5/16/17358774/yanny-laurel-explained |accessdate= May 16, 2018 |work=Vox |date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516224910/https://www.vox.com/2018/5/16/17358774/yanny-laurel-explained |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref> In the brief audio recording, 53% of over 500,000 people answered on a [[Twitter]] poll that they heard a man saying the original word \"Laurel\", while 47% reported hearing a voice saying the name \"Yanny\".{{r|History}} Analysis of the sound frequencies has confirmed that both sets of sounds are present in the mixed recording,<ref name=\"Katz\">{{cite news |title= We Made a Tool So You Can Hear Both Yanny and Laurel |author1= Josh Katz |author2= Jonathan Corum and Jon Huang |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/05/16/upshot/audio-clip-yanny-laurel-debate.html |quote= playing the \"laurel\" clip over speakers and re-recording it introduced noise and exaggerated the higher frequencies. |date= May 16, 2018 |accessdate= 2018-06-01 |newspaper= The New York Times }}</ref> but some users focus on the higher frequency sounds in \"Yanny\" and cannot seem to hear the lower sounds of the word \"Laurel\".\nWhen the audio clip has been slowed to lower frequencies, then the word \"Yanny\" has been heard by more listeners, while faster playback loudens \"Laurel\".\n\n==Background==\nThe mixed re-recording was created by students who played the sound of the word \"laurel\" (a [[laurel wreath]]), while re-recording the playback amid background noise in the room.<ref>{{cite news |title= We Made a Tool So You Can Hear Both Yanny and Laurel |author1= Josh Katz |author2= Jonathan Corum and Jon Huang |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/05/16/upshot/audio-clip-yanny-laurel-debate.html |quote= playing the \u201claurel\u201d clip over speakers and re-recording it introduced noise and exaggerated the higher frequencies. |date=16 May 2018  |newspaper= The New York Times }}</ref>\nThe audio clip of the main word \"laurel\" originated in 2007 from a recording of Jay Aubrey Jones, an opera singer,<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://time.com/5281287/jay-aubrey-jones-laurel-yanny-voice/ |title= Meet the Voice behind That 'Laurel' (or 'Yanny') Clip That's Driving Everyone Nuts |work=Time.com |access-date= May 19, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180519005159/http://time.com/5281287/jay-aubrey-jones-laurel-yanny-voice/ |archivedate= May 19, 2018 }}</ref> who spoke the word \"laurel\"<ref name=vocab>[https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/laurel \"Laurel\" at vocabulary.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516223658/https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/laurel |date=May 16, 2018 }}</ref> as one of 200,000 reference pronunciations produced and published by www.vocabulary.com in 2007.<ref name=History>{{cite news |last1=Salam |first1=Maya |last2=Victor |first2=Daniel |title= Laurel or Yanny? What We Heard From the Experts |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/science/yanny-laurel.html |accessdate= May 18, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date= May 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180517215912/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/science/yanny-laurel.html |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=History2>{{cite news |last1=Matsakis |first1=Louise |title= The True History of 'Yanny' and 'Laurel' |url= https://www.wired.com/story/yanny-and-laurel-true-history/ |work= WIRED |date= May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516200348/https://www.wired.com/story/yanny-and-laurel-true-history/ |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=vocab/> The clip was made at Jones' home using a laptop and microphone, with surrounding foam to help soundproof the recording.<ref name=\"BuzzFeed conspiracy\">{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Virginia |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/virginiahughes/yanny-laurel-audio-conspiracy-theory |title=We Got To The Bottom Of A Geeky Conspiracy Theory About Yanny And Laurel |work=BuzzFeed News |date=May 27, 2018 |accessdate=May 27, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180527194846/https://www.buzzfeed.com/virginiahughes/yanny-laurel-audio-conspiracy-theory |archivedate= May 27, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe discovery of the ambiguity phenomenon is attributed to Katie Hetzel, a 15-year-old freshman at [[Flowery Branch High School]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hIa03TcwDzk Katie Hetzel, 15 yr old Flowery Branch High Freshman interview with Francesca Amiker on 11alive.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529111732/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hIa03TcwDzk |date=May 29, 2018 }} (published to YouTube on May 18, 2018)</ref> near [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], who posted a description publicly on Instagram on May 11, 2018. The illusion reached further popularity when the student's friend posted it on Reddit the next day.<ref name=History/> It was picked up by YouTuber Cloe Feldman on her Twitter account.<ref name=History2/> studies. Studies have shown\n\n==Pop culture==\nNotable individuals who responded to the auditory illusion included [[Ellen DeGeneres]], [[Stephen King]], and [[Chrissy Teigen]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoggatt |first1=Aja |title=Is your favorite celeb a Yanny or a Laurel? |url= http://ew.com/news/2018/05/15/nanny-laurel-celebrity-twitter-reactions/ |accessdate=May 16, 2018 |work= Entertainment Weekly |date=May 15, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Kane |first1=Caitlin |title=Yanny vs. Laurel: What do you hear? |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/yanny-vs-laurel-what-do-you-hear/ |accessdate= May 16, 2018 |work=CBS News |date=May 16, 2018 }}</ref> [[Laurel Halo]] and [[Yanni]], whose names are similar to those given in the auditory illusion, also responded.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gray |first= Julia |title= Yanny Or Laurel: Yanni And Laurel Halo Weigh In |url= https://www.stereogum.com/1996644/yanni-and-laurel-halo-finally-break-their-legendary-silence-about-yanny-or-laurel-meme/news/ |accessdate= May 17, 2018 |work= Stereogum |date= May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180517062855/https://www.stereogum.com/1996644/yanni-and-laurel-halo-finally-break-their-legendary-silence-about-yanny-or-laurel-meme/news/ |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref> In a video released by the [[White House]], various members of the Trump administration reacted to the meme, and President [[Donald Trump]] said, \"I hear covfefe\", as a reference to his \"[[covfefe]]\" tweet the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |title= Laurel, Yanny or ... covfefe? White House joins in on debate |url= http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-laurel-yanny-white-house-video-20180517-story.html |accessdate= May 18, 2018 |work= Chicago Tribune |agency= Associated Press |date= May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Donald Trump weighs in on the Yanny or Laurel debate |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RVAFlCeXQMI |website=YouTube |publisher=Guardian News |accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Guardian]]'', the clip was compared to the 2015 [[The dress|gold/blue dress controversy]].<ref name=\"Watson 2018\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/may/16/yanny-or-laurel-sound-illusion-sets-off-ear-splitting-arguments |title= Laurel or Yanny debate: why do some people hear a different word? |last=Watson |first=Chloe |date=May 17, 2018 |website=the Guardian |access-date= May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180517001023/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/may/16/yanny-or-laurel-sound-illusion-sets-off-ear-splitting-arguments |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref> Several days after the clip became viral, the team at Vocabulary.com added a separate entry for the word \"Yanny\", which contained an audio clip identical to \"Laurel\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's why you're hearing \"Yanny\" \u2013 and why it's technically \"Laurel\" |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/yanny-vs-laurel-debate-sparks-internet-controversy/ |accessdate=May 17, 2018 |work=CBS News |date=May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517152848/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/yanny-vs-laurel-debate-sparks-internet-controversy/ |archivedate=May 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=YannyonVocabulary.com>{{Cite web |url= https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/yanny |title=Yanny - Dictionary Definition : Vocabulary.com |website= www.vocabulary.com |access-date= May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517155654/https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/yanny |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref> Its definition is about the Internet trend.<ref name=\"YannyonVocabulary.com\" /> \n\nOn May 17, a similar viral story grew around a recording of a man saying \"brainstorm\" which many heard as \"green needle\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Molloy |first1=Mark |title=Brainstorm or Green Needle? How the latest audio riddle tricks your brain |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/05/18/brainstorm-green-needle-latest-audio-riddle-tricks-brain/ |accessdate=28 January 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=18 May 2018}}; {{cite news |last1=Cvorak |first1=Monika |last2=Bullock |first2=James  |title=The new Yanny/Laurel: do you hear brainstorm or green needle? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/video/2018/may/18/the-new-yannylaurel-do-you-hear-brainstorm-or-green-needle-video |accessdate=28 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 May 2018}}; {{cite web |url=https://www.digg.com/2018/brainstorm-or-green-needle%3famp=true |title=We Can't Trust Our Ears Anymore Now The 'Brainstorm'/'Green Needle' Auditory Illusion Is Breaking Our Brains |accessdate=May 21, 2018 |work=digg.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521220145/http://digg.com/2018/brainstorm-or-green-needle?amp=true |archivedate=May 21, 2018 }}; {{cite web |title=Beyond Yanny or Laurel: 6 Other Aural Illusions and How They Work |url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/545157/beyond-yanny-laurel-other-aural-illusions-how-they-work |website=www.mentalfloss.com |accessdate=28 January 2020 |language=en |date=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Scientific analysis==\nOn May 16, 2018, a report in ''The New York Times'' noted a spectrogram analysis confirmed how the extra sounds for \"yanny\" can be graphed in the mixed re-recording.<ref name=Katz/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/science/yanny-laurel.html|title=Yanny or Laurel? How a Sound Clip Divided America|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=2018-05-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-10|last2=Victor|first2=Daniel|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The sounds also were simulated by combining syllables of the same Vocabulary.com voice saying the words \"Yangtze\" and \"uncanny\" as a mash-up of sounds which gave a similar spectrogram as the extra sounds graphed in the laurel re-recording.<ref name=Katz/>\n\n[[Benjamin Munson (professor)|Benjamin Munson]], a professor of audiology at the [[University of Minnesota]], suggested that \"Yanny\" can be heard in higher frequencies while \"Laurel\" can be heard in lower frequencies.<ref name=\"Vox\" /> Older people, whose [[Presbycusis|ability to hear higher frequencies is more likely to have degraded]], usually hear \"Laurel\". Kevin Franck, the director of audiology at the Boston hospital [[Massachusetts Eye and Ear]] says that the clip exists on a \"perceptual boundary\" and compared it to the [[Necker Cube]] illusion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ducharme |first1=Jamie |title= An Audiologist Explains Why You Hear 'Yanny' or 'Laurel' \u2014 Or Both |url= http://time.com/5279069/yanny-laurel-explanation/ |accessdate= May 16, 2018 |work=Time |date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180516233138/http://time.com/5279069/yanny-laurel-explanation/ |archivedate=May 16, 2018 }}</ref> Professor David Alais from the University of Sydney's school of psychology also compared the clip to the Necker Cube or the [[Rubin vase|face/vase illusion]], calling it a \"perceptually ambiguous stimulus\".<ref name=\"Watson 2018\" /> Brad Story, a professor of speech, language, and audiology at the [[University of Arizona]] said that the low quality of the recording creates ambiguity.<ref name=CNN>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Amanda |title=Laurel or Yanny? What science has to say |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/15/health/yanny-laurel-audio-social-media-trnd/index.html |accessdate=May 16, 2018 |work=CNN |date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180516033621/https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/15/health/yanny-laurel-audio-social-media-trnd/index.html |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref> Dr. Hans Rutger Bosker, psycholinguist and phonetician at the [[Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics]], showed that it is possible to make the same person hear the same audio clip differently by presenting it in different acoustic contexts: if one hears the ambiguous audio clip after a lead-in sentence without any high frequencies (>1000&nbsp;Hz), this makes the higher frequencies in the following ambiguous audio clip stand out more, making people report \"Yanny\" where they previously maybe heard \"Laurel\".<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/chitchat-about-chatter/201805/the-psychology-laurel-and-yanny |title= The Psychology of Laurel and Yanny |website= Psychology Today |access-date= May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Pitch-shifted versions ===\n{{Listen|type=music|filename=Laurel.ogg|title=\"Yanny or Laurel\" (pitch shifted higher)|description=By pitch shifting the original audio by 20%, \"Laurel\" is clearer.}}\nBy [[pitch shift]]ing the original audio to higher or lower frequencies, the same listener can report different interpretations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gutman |first1=Rachel |title=A Linguist Explains Why 'Laurel' Sounds Like 'Yanny' |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/05/dont-rest-on-your-laurels/560483/ |accessdate= May 17, 2018 |work= The Atlantic |date= May 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180516213706/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/05/dont-rest-on-your-laurels/560483/ |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' released an interactive tool on their website that changes the pitch of the recording in real-time. The interactive slider allows the recording to be played back at any pitch between 3 semitones higher (to help the listener hear \"Laurel\"), and 6 semitones lower (to help the listener hear \"Yanny\").<ref name=Katz/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet}}\n* [[The dress]]\n* [[List of Internet phenomena]]\n* [[Auditory illusion]]\n* [[Malapropism]]\n* [[McGurk effect]]\n* [[Mondegreen]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/yanny Vocabulary.com definition for \"yanny\"]\n\n{{Auditory illusions}}\n\n[[Category:2007 works]]\n[[Category:2018 in science]]\n[[Category:Auditory illusions]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2018]]\n[[Category:May 2018 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc}}\n{{redirect|Yanny|other uses|Yanni (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|voice recording containing an auditory illusion and made popular in May 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Listen|type=Music|filename=YannyLaurel.ogg|title=Laurel|description=This low quality recording of the pronunciation of \"Laurel\", which went viral on Twitter, enhances the illusion according to Brad Story.<ref name=CNN/>{{Verify source|date=May 2018}}}}\n'''\"Yanny or Laurel\"''' is an [[auditory illusion]] of a re-recording of a vocabulary word plus added background sounds, also mixed into the recording, which became popular in May 2018.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news |last= Kirby |first=Jen |title= Why you hear \"Laurel\" or \"Yanny\" in that viral audio clip, explained |url= https://www.vox.com/2018/5/16/17358774/yanny-laurel-explained |accessdate= May 16, 2018 |work=Vox |date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516224910/https://www.vox.com/2018/5/16/17358774/yanny-laurel-explained |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref> In the brief audio recording, 53% of over 500,000 people answered on a [[Twitter]] poll that they heard a man saying the original word \"Laurel\", while 47% reported hearing a voice saying the name \"Yanny\".{{r|History}} Analysis of the sound frequencies has confirmed that both sets of sounds are present in the mixed recording,<ref name=\"Katz\">{{cite news |title= We Made a Tool So You Can Hear Both Yanny and Laurel |author1= Josh Katz |author2= Jonathan Corum and Jon Huang |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/05/16/upshot/audio-clip-yanny-laurel-debate.html |quote= playing the \"laurel\" clip over speakers and re-recording it introduced noise and exaggerated the higher frequencies. |date= May 16, 2018 |accessdate= 2018-06-01 |newspaper= The New York Times }}</ref> but some users focus on the higher frequency sounds in \"Yanny\" and cannot seem to hear the lower sounds of the word \"Laurel\".\nWhen the audio clip has been slowed to lower frequencies, then the word \"Yanny\" has been heard by more listeners, while faster playback loudens \"Laurel\".\n\n==Background==\nThe mixed re-recording was created by students who played the sound of the word \"laurel\" (a [[laurel wreath]]), while re-recording the playback amid background noise in the room.<ref>{{cite news |title= We Made a Tool So You Can Hear Both Yanny and Laurel |author1= Josh Katz |author2= Jonathan Corum and Jon Huang |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/05/16/upshot/audio-clip-yanny-laurel-debate.html |quote= playing the \u201claurel\u201d clip over speakers and re-recording it introduced noise and exaggerated the higher frequencies. |date=16 May 2018  |newspaper= The New York Times }}</ref>\nThe audio clip of the main word \"laurel\" originated in 2007 from a recording of Jay Aubrey Jones, an opera singer,<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://time.com/5281287/jay-aubrey-jones-laurel-yanny-voice/ |title= Meet the Voice behind That 'Laurel' (or 'Yanny') Clip That's Driving Everyone Nuts |work=Time.com |access-date= May 19, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180519005159/http://time.com/5281287/jay-aubrey-jones-laurel-yanny-voice/ |archivedate= May 19, 2018 }}</ref> who spoke the word \"laurel\"<ref name=vocab>[https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/laurel \"Laurel\" at vocabulary.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516223658/https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/laurel |date=May 16, 2018 }}</ref> as one of 200,000 reference pronunciations produced and published by www.vocabulary.com in 2007.<ref name=History>{{cite news |last1=Salam |first1=Maya |last2=Victor |first2=Daniel |title= Laurel or Yanny? What We Heard From the Experts |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/science/yanny-laurel.html |accessdate= May 18, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date= May 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180517215912/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/science/yanny-laurel.html |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=History2>{{cite news |last1=Matsakis |first1=Louise |title= The True History of 'Yanny' and 'Laurel' |url= https://www.wired.com/story/yanny-and-laurel-true-history/ |work= WIRED |date= May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516200348/https://www.wired.com/story/yanny-and-laurel-true-history/ |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=vocab/> The clip was made at Jones' home using a laptop and microphone, with surrounding foam to help soundproof the recording.<ref name=\"BuzzFeed conspiracy\">{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Virginia |url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/virginiahughes/yanny-laurel-audio-conspiracy-theory |title=We Got To The Bottom Of A Geeky Conspiracy Theory About Yanny And Laurel |work=BuzzFeed News |date=May 27, 2018 |accessdate=May 27, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180527194846/https://www.buzzfeed.com/virginiahughes/yanny-laurel-audio-conspiracy-theory |archivedate= May 27, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe discovery of the ambiguity phenomenon is attributed to Katie Hetzel, a 15-year-old freshman at [[Flowery Branch High School]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hIa03TcwDzk Katie Hetzel, 15 yr old Flowery Branch High Freshman interview with Francesca Amiker on 11alive.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529111732/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hIa03TcwDzk |date=May 29, 2018 }} (published to YouTube on May 18, 2018)</ref> near [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], who posted a description publicly on Instagram on May 11, 2018. The illusion reached further popularity when the student's friend posted it on Reddit the next day.<ref name=History/> It was picked up by YouTuber Cloe Feldman on her Twitter account.<ref name=History2/>\n\n==Pop culture==\nNotable individuals who responded to the auditory illusion included [[Ellen DeGeneres]], [[Stephen King]], and [[Chrissy Teigen]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoggatt |first1=Aja |title=Is your favorite celeb a Yanny or a Laurel? |url= http://ew.com/news/2018/05/15/nanny-laurel-celebrity-twitter-reactions/ |accessdate=May 16, 2018 |work= Entertainment Weekly |date=May 15, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Kane |first1=Caitlin |title=Yanny vs. Laurel: What do you hear? |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/yanny-vs-laurel-what-do-you-hear/ |accessdate= May 16, 2018 |work=CBS News |date=May 16, 2018 }}</ref> [[Laurel Halo]] and [[Yanni]], whose names are similar to those given in the auditory illusion, also responded.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gray |first= Julia |title= Yanny Or Laurel: Yanni And Laurel Halo Weigh In |url= https://www.stereogum.com/1996644/yanni-and-laurel-halo-finally-break-their-legendary-silence-about-yanny-or-laurel-meme/news/ |accessdate= May 17, 2018 |work= Stereogum |date= May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180517062855/https://www.stereogum.com/1996644/yanni-and-laurel-halo-finally-break-their-legendary-silence-about-yanny-or-laurel-meme/news/ |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref> In a video released by the [[White House]], various members of the Trump administration reacted to the meme, and President [[Donald Trump]] said, \"I hear covfefe\", as a reference to his \"[[covfefe]]\" tweet the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |title= Laurel, Yanny or ... covfefe? White House joins in on debate |url= http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-laurel-yanny-white-house-video-20180517-story.html |accessdate= May 18, 2018 |work= Chicago Tribune |agency= Associated Press |date= May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Donald Trump weighs in on the Yanny or Laurel debate |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RVAFlCeXQMI |website=YouTube |publisher=Guardian News |accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Guardian]]'', the clip was compared to the 2015 [[The dress|gold/blue dress controversy]].<ref name=\"Watson 2018\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/may/16/yanny-or-laurel-sound-illusion-sets-off-ear-splitting-arguments |title= Laurel or Yanny debate: why do some people hear a different word? |last=Watson |first=Chloe |date=May 17, 2018 |website=the Guardian |access-date= May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180517001023/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/may/16/yanny-or-laurel-sound-illusion-sets-off-ear-splitting-arguments |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref> Several days after the clip became viral, the team at Vocabulary.com added a separate entry for the word \"Yanny\", which contained an audio clip identical to \"Laurel\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's why you're hearing \"Yanny\" \u2013 and why it's technically \"Laurel\" |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/yanny-vs-laurel-debate-sparks-internet-controversy/ |accessdate=May 17, 2018 |work=CBS News |date=May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517152848/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/yanny-vs-laurel-debate-sparks-internet-controversy/ |archivedate=May 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=YannyonVocabulary.com>{{Cite web |url= https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/yanny |title=Yanny - Dictionary Definition : Vocabulary.com |website= www.vocabulary.com |access-date= May 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517155654/https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/yanny |archivedate= May 17, 2018 }}</ref> Its definition is about the Internet trend.<ref name=\"YannyonVocabulary.com\" /> \n\nOn May 17, a similar viral story grew around a recording of a man saying \"brainstorm\" which many heard as \"green needle\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Molloy |first1=Mark |title=Brainstorm or Green Needle? How the latest audio riddle tricks your brain |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/05/18/brainstorm-green-needle-latest-audio-riddle-tricks-brain/ |accessdate=28 January 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=18 May 2018}}; {{cite news |last1=Cvorak |first1=Monika |last2=Bullock |first2=James  |title=The new Yanny/Laurel: do you hear brainstorm or green needle? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/video/2018/may/18/the-new-yannylaurel-do-you-hear-brainstorm-or-green-needle-video |accessdate=28 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 May 2018}}; {{cite web |url=https://www.digg.com/2018/brainstorm-or-green-needle%3famp=true |title=We Can't Trust Our Ears Anymore Now The 'Brainstorm'/'Green Needle' Auditory Illusion Is Breaking Our Brains |accessdate=May 21, 2018 |work=digg.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521220145/http://digg.com/2018/brainstorm-or-green-needle?amp=true |archivedate=May 21, 2018 }}; {{cite web |title=Beyond Yanny or Laurel: 6 Other Aural Illusions and How They Work |url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/545157/beyond-yanny-laurel-other-aural-illusions-how-they-work |website=www.mentalfloss.com |accessdate=28 January 2020 |language=en |date=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Scientific analysis==\nOn May 16, 2018, a report in ''The New York Times'' noted a spectrogram analysis confirmed how the extra sounds for \"yanny\" can be graphed in the mixed re-recording.<ref name=Katz/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/science/yanny-laurel.html|title=Yanny or Laurel? How a Sound Clip Divided America|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=2018-05-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-10|last2=Victor|first2=Daniel|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The sounds also were simulated by combining syllables of the same Vocabulary.com voice saying the words \"Yangtze\" and \"uncanny\" as a mash-up of sounds which gave a similar spectrogram as the extra sounds graphed in the laurel re-recording.<ref name=Katz/>\n\n[[Benjamin Munson (professor)|Benjamin Munson]], a professor of audiology at the [[University of Minnesota]], suggested that \"Yanny\" can be heard in higher frequencies while \"Laurel\" can be heard in lower frequencies.<ref name=\"Vox\" /> Older people, whose [[Presbycusis|ability to hear higher frequencies is more likely to have degraded]], usually hear \"Laurel\". Kevin Franck, the director of audiology at the Boston hospital [[Massachusetts Eye and Ear]] says that the clip exists on a \"perceptual boundary\" and compared it to the [[Necker Cube]] illusion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ducharme |first1=Jamie |title= An Audiologist Explains Why You Hear 'Yanny' or 'Laurel' \u2014 Or Both |url= http://time.com/5279069/yanny-laurel-explanation/ |accessdate= May 16, 2018 |work=Time |date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180516233138/http://time.com/5279069/yanny-laurel-explanation/ |archivedate=May 16, 2018 }}</ref> Professor David Alais from the University of Sydney's school of psychology also compared the clip to the Necker Cube or the [[Rubin vase|face/vase illusion]], calling it a \"perceptually ambiguous stimulus\".<ref name=\"Watson 2018\" /> Brad Story, a professor of speech, language, and audiology at the [[University of Arizona]] said that the low quality of the recording creates ambiguity.<ref name=CNN>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Amanda |title=Laurel or Yanny? What science has to say |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/15/health/yanny-laurel-audio-social-media-trnd/index.html |accessdate=May 16, 2018 |work=CNN |date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180516033621/https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/15/health/yanny-laurel-audio-social-media-trnd/index.html |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref> Dr. Hans Rutger Bosker, psycholinguist and phonetician at the [[Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics]], showed that it is possible to make the same person hear the same audio clip differently by presenting it in different acoustic contexts: if one hears the ambiguous audio clip after a lead-in sentence without any high frequencies (>1000&nbsp;Hz), this makes the higher frequencies in the following ambiguous audio clip stand out more, making people report \"Yanny\" where they previously maybe heard \"Laurel\".<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/chitchat-about-chatter/201805/the-psychology-laurel-and-yanny |title= The Psychology of Laurel and Yanny |website= Psychology Today |access-date= May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Pitch-shifted versions ===\n{{Listen|type=music|filename=Laurel.ogg|title=\"Yanny or Laurel\" (pitch shifted higher)|description=By pitch shifting the original audio by 20%, \"Laurel\" is clearer.}}\nBy [[pitch shift]]ing the original audio to higher or lower frequencies, the same listener can report different interpretations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gutman |first1=Rachel |title=A Linguist Explains Why 'Laurel' Sounds Like 'Yanny' |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/05/dont-rest-on-your-laurels/560483/ |accessdate= May 17, 2018 |work= The Atlantic |date= May 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180516213706/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/05/dont-rest-on-your-laurels/560483/ |archivedate= May 16, 2018 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' released an interactive tool on their website that changes the pitch of the recording in real-time. The interactive slider allows the recording to be played back at any pitch between 3 semitones higher (to help the listener hear \"Laurel\"), and 6 semitones lower (to help the listener hear \"Yanny\").<ref name=Katz/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet}}\n* [[The dress]]\n* [[List of Internet phenomena]]\n* [[Auditory illusion]]\n* [[Malapropism]]\n* [[McGurk effect]]\n* [[Mondegreen]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.vocabulary.com/dictionary/yanny Vocabulary.com definition for \"yanny\"]\n\n{{Auditory illusions}}\n\n[[Category:2007 works]]\n[[Category:2018 in science]]\n[[Category:Auditory illusions]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2018]]\n[[Category:May 2018 events]]\n", "name_user": "94.204.145.66", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Update)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yanny_or_Laurel"}
{"title_page": "George Iles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga Rugby\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =\n|ru_triesA           =0\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =0\n|ru_teamB            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = \n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Mrs H. Iles and Albert Iles whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League Playing Career==\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n==Rugby Union Playing Career==\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In September of 1920 Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1921 Iles continued to play for Tauranga, scoring a try in a match against Mercury Bay <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. However on the 16th of August he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the Tauranga area in 1922. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the season on August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Then in September he again went on the attack, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles was playing rugby again and represented Tauranga against Hamilton<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in Te Puke, Whakatane, and Taneatua and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga Rugby\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =\n|ru_triesA           =0\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =0\n|ru_teamB            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = \n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Mrs H. Iles and Albert Iles whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League Playing Career==\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n==Rugby Union Playing Career==\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In September of 1920 Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1921 Iles continued to play for Tauranga, scoring a try in a match against Mercury Bay <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. However on the 16th of August he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the Tauranga area in 1922. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the season on August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Then in September he again went on the attack, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles was playing rugby again and represented Tauranga against Hamilton<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBusiness Life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
